
TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Resource-Based Theory of the Firm
AU  - Barney, Jay B.
Y1  - 1996/10/01
PY  - 1996
DA  - 1996/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/orsc.7.5.469
DO  - 10.1287/orsc.7.5.469
T2  - Organization Science
JF  - Organization Science
JO  - Organization Science
SP  - 469
EP  - 469
VL  - 7
IS  - 5
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Interest in the resource-based view of the firm continues to grow in the field of business policy and strategy. Recently, most of this interest seems to have been focused on understanding the empirical implications of this theory and especially on how a firm's resources and capabilities can affect its performance. Evaluating the empirical implications of the resource based view is, of course, a worthwhile endeavor. We present an overview of contributions in this issue.
AB  - Interest in the resource-based view of the firm continues to grow in the field of business policy and strategy. Recently, most of this interest seems to have been focused on understanding the empirical implications of this theory and especially on how a firm's resources and capabilities can affect its performance. Evaluating the empirical implications of the resource based view is, of course, a worthwhile endeavor. We present an overview of contributions in this issue.
